{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "PolarAerosol",
        "description": "ModelingToolkit implementation of the Polar atmospheric aerosol size distribution, from Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd ed., Chapter 8 (\"Properties of the Atmospheric Aerosol\"), Table 8.3. The Polar distribution is a preset of the multi-modal lognormal AerosolDistribution model: three lognormal modes (N = [21.7, 0.186, 3.0e-4] cm^-3, D_g = [0.138, 0.75, 8.6] um, log10 sigma = [0.245, 0.300, 0.291]) — a dilute accumulation mode plus two coarse modes characteristic of the very clean polar atmosphere. The model represents the aerosol number, surface-area and volume distributions as a sum of the three modes (Eq. 8.54) and reports the total number/surface/volume concentrations, the mode-1 Hatch-Choate diameters, and the vertical aerosol mass profile (Eq. 8.55). Migrated from Aerosol.jl PolarAerosol, a preset wrapper around AerosolDistribution(3). Purely algebraic: ten observed outputs, no differential states, an empty equations array. The upstream length-n_modes array parameters are scalarized at n_modes = 3 with the Polar Table 8.3 mode parameters as defaults.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "size-distribution",
            "lognormal",
            "polar",
            "seinfeld_pandis_ch8"
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "PolarAerosol": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Chapter 8, \"Properties of the Atmospheric Aerosol\". Multi-modal lognormal size distribution: Eq. 8.54 (number), 8.49/8.50 (surface area), 8.52/8.53 (volume); Hatch-Choate diameters Eq. 8.44/8.50/8.53; total moments Eq. 8.41 with Eq. 8.5/8.7; vertical mass profile Eq. 8.55. Mode parameters are the Polar entry of Table 8.3.",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1:src/size_distribution.jl:262\n\nUpstream `PolarAerosol(; name=:PolarAerosol)` is a thin preset wrapper that calls `AerosolDistribution(3; name, N_vals, D_g_vals, logsigma_vals)` with the Polar mode parameters of Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3. It returns a flat MTK `System` — not a hierarchical composition — identical in structure to the base `AerosolDistribution` component but with the three array `@parameters` N / D_g / logsigma defaulted to the Polar values. The migration is therefore a standalone copy of `components/aerosol/size/aerosol_distribution.esm` with the nine scalarized mode-parameter defaults replaced; the ten observed-output expressions and the empty equations array are unchanged.\n\nMigration form: observed-form, matching `aerosol_distribution.esm`. The base component carries two `@constants` (pi_c = pi, ln10 = log(10)), the length-n_modes array `@parameters` N / D_g / logsigma plus the scalar `@parameters` D_p, z, H_p, and ten time-indexed `@variables` (n_N_o, n_S_o, n_V_o, N_t, S_t, V_t, D_s, D_v, D_bar, M_z) each defined by one algebraic `lhs ~ rhs` equation whose RHS references only parameters and constants. Per the purely-algebraic migration rule each output is encoded as `type: observed` with its defining relation in the `expression` field and the `equations` array is empty.\n\nArray scalarization: as in the base migration the length-3 array parameters N, D_g, logsigma are scalarized into nine scalar parameters N_1..N_3, D_g_1..D_g_3, logsigma_1..logsigma_3 and each `sum(... for i in 1:n_modes)` is unrolled into an explicit three-term sum. PolarAerosol is a three-mode distribution, so n_modes = 3 is exact (not a default truncation). The `.esm` array-variable path emits `getindex` nodes (tracked upstream as gt-p3ep), which is why the scalarized form is used.\n\nPolar defaults (Table 8.3, Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Chapter 8): N = [21.7, 0.186, 3.0e-4] cm^-3 -> [2.17e7, 1.86e5, 3.0e2] m^-3 (x1e6); D_g = [0.138, 0.75, 8.6] um -> [1.38e-7, 7.5e-7, 8.6e-6] m (x1e-6); logsigma = [0.245, 0.300, 0.291] (log10 of the geometric standard deviation, dimensionless). The polar aerosol is extremely dilute: mode 1 (D_g = 0.138 um) is an accumulation mode and modes 2-3 (D_g = 0.75, 8.6 um) are coarse modes, with the mode-3 number concentration only 3.0e-4 cm^-3. D_p defaults to 1.0e-7 m (0.1 um) — the evaluation diameter used by the upstream test suite, consistent with `aerosol_distribution.esm`; z = 0 and H_p = 1000 m are the upstream scalar defaults.\n\nConstant handling: pi_c and ln10 are upstream `@constants`. The ESS schema has no constant variable type, so each migrates as a `type: parameter` with a fixed evaluated numeric default (pi_c = 3.141592653589793, ln10 = 2.302585092994046); the symbols are kept in the expressions. ln10 converts the log10-based logsigma to natural-log form: ln(sigma_g) = logsigma * ln10.\n\nPruned parameter: the base component's `@parameter rho_p` (particle density, default 1500 kg/m^3) appears in none of the ten equations and is omitted per the unused-parameter rule, as in `aerosol_distribution.esm`.\n\nTests: polar_default_distribution pins all ten outputs at the Polar defaults (D_p = 1.0e-7 m). The remaining six tests are the preset-independent equation-correctness tests carried over verbatim from `aerosol_distribution.esm` — they override the mode parameters (a single mode with modes 2 & 3 switched off, the lognormal one-sigma points, the near-monodisperse Hatch-Choate limit) or the vertical-profile parameters, so their expected values do not depend on the Polar defaults and verify the migrated equations directly. The Urban/Marine/Remote-continental preset-override tests of the base file are dropped as off-topic for the Polar preset.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-9): the component is purely algebraic with no ODE integration. Each output is a finite composition of +, *, /, ^, sqrt, exp and log10 in float64 (round-off ~1e-16 relative); rel=1e-9 leaves seven orders of magnitude of headroom and absorbs any associativity difference in the n-ary sums. The polar_default_distribution expected values were generated with the canonical ESS Python runner (earthsci_toolkit.simulate) — the same pathway as the inline-test gate.\n\nUnits: descriptive only; the ESS runners do no dimensional analysis. Units are copied from the upstream `unit` metadata verbatim (n_S_o / S_t in m^-1, n_V_o / V_t / M_z dimensionless)."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-09
            },
            "variables": {
                "π_c": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 3.141592653589793,
                    "description": "Pi (mathematical constant). Upstream MTK @constants entry pi_c = pi; the ESS schema has no constant variable type, so it migrates as a fixed-default parameter with the evaluated numeric value."
                },
                "ln10": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 2.302585092994046,
                    "description": "Natural logarithm of 10. Upstream MTK @constants entry ln10 = log(10.0); migrated as a fixed-default parameter. Converts the log10-based geometric standard deviations logsigma to natural-log form, ln(sigma_g) = logsigma * ln10."
                },
                "N_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 21700000.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 1 (accumulation mode). Upstream array @parameter N[1] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (21.7 cm^-3 converted to m^-3 by x1e6)."
                },
                "N_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 186000.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 2 (coarse mode). Upstream array @parameter N[2] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (0.186 cm^-3 converted to m^-3 by x1e6)."
                },
                "N_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 300.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 3 (coarse mode). Upstream array @parameter N[3] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (3.0e-4 cm^-3 converted to m^-3 by x1e6)."
                },
                "D_g_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1.38e-07,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 1 (accumulation mode). Upstream array @parameter D_g[1] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (0.138 um converted to m by x1e-6)."
                },
                "D_g_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 7.5e-07,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 2 (coarse mode). Upstream array @parameter D_g[2] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (0.75 um converted to m by x1e-6)."
                },
                "D_g_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 8.6e-06,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 3 (coarse mode). Upstream array @parameter D_g[3] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (8.6 um converted to m by x1e-6)."
                },
                "logσ_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.245,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 1 (accumulation mode) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logσ[1] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "logσ_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.3,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 2 (coarse mode) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logσ[2] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "logσ_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.291,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 3 (coarse mode) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logσ[3] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Polar distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "D_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1e-07,
                    "description": "Particle diameter at which the number, surface-area and volume distribution densities n_N_o/n_S_o/n_V_o are evaluated. The upstream base AerosolDistribution declares D_p with no default; 1.0e-7 m (0.1 um) is adopted here — the diameter the upstream test suite evaluates the distributions at, consistent with components/aerosol/size/aerosol_distribution.esm."
                },
                "z": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Altitude above the surface, used by the vertical mass profile M_z. Default 0 m (surface). Upstream @parameter z = 0.0."
                },
                "H_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Aerosol mass scale height in the vertical profile M_z = exp(-z/H_p). Default 1000 m. Upstream @parameter H_p = 1000.0."
                },
                "n_N_o": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "Number distribution density dN/d(log D_p) at the evaluation diameter D_p — the sum of n_modes lognormal modes (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Eq. 8.54).",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "+",
                        "args": [
